From 3ba9ebeb40d6a1a2c40b8f3ae9d45f4d8dba9313 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Felicitas Pojtinger <felicitas@pojtinger.com>
Date: Sat, 16 May 2026 00:45:21 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] docs: Add section on groups fighting for digital rights

Signed-off-by: Felicitas Pojtinger <felicitas@pojtinger.com>
---
diff --git a/outline.md b/outline.md
index 0533e6a6ca20ea3be979621cbf41a2abe8adc87a..6b2d3c468d93d38f16a2298163416ba9059da7d7 100644
--- a/outline.md
+++ b/outline.md
@@ -21,11 +21,44 @@   - Usually this focuses on formats and servers, which is good, but for technology to be more resilient I think we need to go one step further and focus on our personal computing tools - phones, tablets, laptops, TVs, routers, printers, etc. - too
 - Groups that are fighting back and how
   - Many organizations are working on fighting back on this, esp. for personal computing devices, but the most interesting one in my opinion is the Modal Collective
   - (I am not affiliated with the Modal Collective)
+  - "Modal is a new independent collective building emancipatory software for an uncertain world"
+  - "We are working towards a secure free software operating system accessible to everyone, with a solid ecosystem of apps that support multi-device sync and collaboration"
+  - Goals and principles can be found at https://modal.cx/principles/
 - Goals
+  - A Secure Free Desktop
+  - Phones without Monopolies
+  - Local-First Collaboration
+  - Image-Based OSes
+  - Hardware Longevity
+  - Ecosystem of Respectful Apps
 - Principles
+  - Based on the original Software Freedom definition, GNOME's focus on inclusivity and maintainability, the local-first research from Ink & Switch and the holistic lifecycle view from Permacomputing
+  - Software Freedom
+  - Built For Everyone
+  - Design-First
+  - Vertical Integration
+  - Collapse Awareness
+  - Adversarial Security Posture
+  - Post-Internet
+  - Post-Web
+  - Upstream-First
+  - Respect for Attention
 - A stack of emancipatory software
-- Demo: Reflection on laptop, tablet and phone
+  - In digital sovereignty, we often talk about a digitally sovereign stack (example: EuroStack, DeutschlandStack)
+  - Stack in this case refers to a collection of technologies that can be stitched together to solve problems in technology
+  - In this case, we want a stack that supports the goals and principles from above
+  - Introduced in https://modal.cx/blog/sovereign-mobile-stack/
+  - App distribution: Flathub
+  - Platform: Flatpak, GTK, Adwaita, GNOME and XDG portals
+  - Services: CRDTs, p2panda and iro
+  - System: Wayland, Pipewire, NetworkManager, ModemManager, systemd and Linux
+  - More concrete info on this later
+- Demo: Reflection on laptop, tablet and phone running GNOME OS
+  - https://modal.cx/reflection/
+  - A collaborative note taking app that works with and without the internet
+  - Uses the Sovereign Mobile Stack mentioned above
 - How to Develop GNOME apps
+  - Let's find out how you can write apps like Reflection too
   - GNOME project intro
   - GNOME HIG intro
   - GTK and GNOME intro

